<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Transport Select Committee:  Inquiry into Safety at Level Crossings</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Written evidence from </span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Peter G Rayner</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> (SLC 003)</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">INTRODUCTION.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">1.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We have many </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">years’ experience</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of Level Crossing design, maintenance and operation and we have both given evidence at a number of Inquiries </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">concerning</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> rail safety.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Notably</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Lord Cullens Inquiries into the Paddington Accident and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Professor</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Uff’s Inquiry into the Southall train crash, an</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">d many others.  Additionally have </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">chaired or</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> been members of countless Inquiries into railway accidents.  Our CV’s are available if required.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 10pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">1.2 We are offering this evidence because we have been involved in two recent accidents which        concern level</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> crossing operation.  In addition we expressed concerns regarding the safety of a level </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">crossing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in Nottingham in a detailed private correspondence with the Office of Rail Regulation (ORR) which correspondence others chose to put in the public domain.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">1.3 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We are aware reference to our involvement has been mentioned by the Union TSSA in a  written submission from the General Secretary Manuel Cortes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  Also that our correspondence with the ORR has been forwarded to the Rail Accident and Inquiry Bureau (RAIB) i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">n connection with yet another Level Crossing Incident.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">1.4 It should be known we have not written this submission on behalf of nor in collusion with any other party and do so only in the interests of railway safety.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 35.45pt; text-align:center; text-indent:-17.45pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">THE SPECIFIC POINTS REQUIRING AN OPINIO</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">N.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">2.1</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Are current safety measures at Level Crossings adequate?  How should they be improved?</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2.1.1 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The regulations presently in place for signalled level crossings of various specified types is adequate.  The position could be improved by a review to ensure all crossings are in fact signalled </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in accordance with the regulations</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the required </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">elec</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">trical or mechanical locking is in place.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2.1.2 Examples exist, notably illustrated by the Moreton on Lugg</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> accident where adequate protection was not in place.  This is a key issue and our concern is the culture that is now developing in the railway industry.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2.1.3 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Following the Clapham Accident</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> on 12</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Dec 1988 Antony Hidden QC made recommendations that were</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> accepted by the industry.  One of the most important was No 50 which stated:  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">“BR</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> shall ensure that the organisational framework exists to prevent commercial considerations of a business led railway from compromising safety”</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It is our view that commercia</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">l considerations surrounding the installation of Approach Locking, a standard procedure, prevented</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that safe system being applied </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">espite knowledge within the industry that it was missing.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-21.25pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">2.2 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">In addition to Bridges and underpasses what other cost effectiv</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">e measures can be introduced to replace or improve safety at Level Crossings?</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2.2.1 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The safety of footpath crossings remains an area of concern.  Modern trains are faster and qu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">iet</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">er as investment takes place in new rolling stock.  Commercial consideration</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s must not inhibit the provision of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Red</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">/</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Green</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> warning lights and audible warnings </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">being provided.  Complaints of noise from local residents should not result in audible warnings being reduced.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2.2.2 In the case of Bayles and Wylies Crossing on Nottingham</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Tramway, due to public complaints and indeed commercial considerations a contrived Risk Assessment allowed a deeply flawed arrangement to be put in place.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2.2.3 Elsewhere on the Tramway</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">c</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rossings have been dealt with correctly and safely.  This Crossing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> could have remain</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ed </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> a crossing, provided it </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">was</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> correctly signed and installed.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2.2.4 The correspondence surrounding this case is referred to in 1.2 of this evidence.  (We assume the Committee has the correspondence from others.)</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-17.45pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">2.3 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">How should expendi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ture on improving safety at level crossings be prioriti</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">sed</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> in relation to other demands on the rail budget?</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2.3.1 We have no views to express on this difficult issue other than to acknowledge the problem and be thankful that we no longer have to address it</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  However the situation might be improved if the costs of improving or removing level crossings could be shared by road budgets if the net effect of bridges or underpasses reflected improvements to vehicle and pedestrian flows.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2.3.2 It might be possible </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">for the provision of basic safety interlockings to be installed in a less costly way by not using expensive high technology solutions.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2.3.3 Too often assessments for simple procedures produce prohibitive costs to the overall detriment</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of a safe railway.  However, to attempt to now “turn the clock back” is to expose oneself to criticism and being “out of touch”.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-14.15pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">2.4 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Is Network Rail giving sufficient priority at level crossings?</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2.4.1 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Firstly we accept the historical practices and acknowledge Level Crossings for pedestrians in particular are a difficult area because custom and practice, design and installation has grown up over more than 100 years.  Thus an arrangement in one part of th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e country is different from that in another location particularly with methods of locking wicket gates and other devices.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2.4.2 The accident at Elsenham in 2005 and more recent examples indicate there is a need for the safe bringing together of systems to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ensure safety is paramount.  The Elsenham case points to a cost cutting </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">exercise</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in that only one side of the line was it possible to purchase </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">tickets.  Thus the children crossed the line </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to purchase tickets before boarding the train</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">resulting in their dea</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">th.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2.4.3 An in house review of different geographical locations, the history and position of level crossings in those different locations with a view to best procedure would be sensible.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2.4.4 Network Rail we believe is addressing this problem, details ar</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e not </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">known</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to us but we would not </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">recommend the employment of Consultants.  Expertise exists within Network Rail to address the issue which in view </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">f the different types in existence is a difficult one to address.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2.4.5 In this context we believe the pre</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">sent risks model used by the Industry (ORR and NR) called ACRAM (All Level Crossing Risk Model) is flawed in that it covers in great detail road and pedestrian user but pays little attention to Rail levels of traffic, frequency and speed of trains.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-14.15pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">2.5 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Government policy and regulatory action by the Office of Rail Regulation (ORR) in relation to safety and level crossings adequate?  What more should the Government and ORR do?</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2.5.1 Care must be taken to ensure there is clear water between the Engineers of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> similar professions employed within each organisation.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2.5.2 One of the problems arising more and more is the lessening of the role of Railway Operator.  The Engineering culture is paramount and it has been forgotten that traditionally railway safety was </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">vested in the Superintendent of the Line, latterly known as the Chief Operating Manager, a qualified operator with the equivalent knowledge comparable with the ticket of a Master Mariner at sea.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2.5.3 That office had to work with three engi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">neering disci</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">pli</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nes, Mechanical and Electrical Engineers, Civil Engineers and Signalling Engineers, all of whom are different and equally important.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2.5.4 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">That culture has to a great extent has been lost</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  For example the decision not to provide vital interlocking at More</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ton on Lugg was taken without any discussions with railway operating experts.  It was also taken without any detailed knowledge on the risks of human error.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We believe both organisations </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">i.e.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> ORR and NR are fit for purpose and have difficult but different</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> tasks.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2.5.5 It is our view</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that operating expertise should reside within NR and not be left to the ORR to pick up.  Historically the industry </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">prided itself in its professionalism and felt shame if found wanting  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">by the Railway Inspectorate, the predecess</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ors of the ORR.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">2.6 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">How should the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">legislation governing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> level crossings be updated?</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2.6.1 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There is</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> no need for further legislation </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">unless</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> it is thought extra powers should be given to ensure land owners give up little used farm crossings if sensible al</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ternative routes exist for them to use their land.  Many of these crossings date back to the late nineteenth century.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">2.7 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">How should public awareness of safety at level crossings be improved?</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2.7.1 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">On-going</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> publicity such as school visits, posters, adverts</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">etc.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and perhaps television campaigns regarding reckless motoring.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">August 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>